#### **Explanation**

If the coordinates of two points are (x1, y1) and (x2, y2), then their slope is defined as:

	Slope, m = (y2-y1)/(x2-x1)

And if the slopes of multiple points are the same, it means that they're all in the same line (collinear).

To solve this problem, let's compare the slope of (x1, y1) & (x2, y2) points with the slope of (x2, y2) & (x3, y3), and check if they're equal.

	slope of (x1,y1) & (x2,y2) == slope of (x2,y2) & (x3,y3)
i.e,

	(y2-y1)/(x2-x1) == (y3-y2)/(x3-x2)
or,

	(y2-y1)*(x3-x2) == (y3-y2)*(x2-x1)

This form of the equation will avoid us from the 'denominator is 0' issue. 

In the code, we keep the first two points fixed and we compare the collinearity of the third point with the first two points. If the slopes match, then they're in a straight line. 


