# Approach
- If there are **only 2 points**, then **return true**, since a line can be drawn through any 2 points.

- The approach will be as follows. **We will draw a line from the first two points and check if the other points pass through it**.

- If the **x coordinate for the first two points is the same**, then the **line will be parallel to the y-axis**. Therefore, it is enough to check that the x of all other points also coincide with the current one.

- If the **y coordinate for the first two points is the same**, then the **line will be parallel to the x-axis**. Therefore, it is enough to check that the y of all other points also coincide with the current one.

- If the **abscissas and ordinates for the first two points don't coincide**, then **the line will need to be built in a different way**.

**The equation of a straight line** has the form: $ y = k \cdot x + b $.

Compose a **system of equations for two points**:

$
\begin{cases}
y_1 = k \cdot x_1 + b \\
y_2 = k \cdot x_2 + b 
\end{cases}
$

The **unknowns** are the coefficients **k** and **b**. Let's **rewrite** the system in the following form:

$
\begin{cases}
k \cdot x_1 + 1 \cdot b = y_1 \\
k \cdot x_2 + 1 \cdot b = y_2
\end{cases}
$

System in **matrix form**:

$
\begin{pmatrix}
    x_1 & 1\\ 
    x_2 & 1 
\end{pmatrix}
\times
\begin{pmatrix}
    k\\ 
    b   
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
    y_1\\ 
    y_2   
\end{pmatrix}
$

This system, for example, can be solved by the **Cramer method**:

$
k =
\frac{
\begin{vmatrix}
  y_1 & 1\\
  y_2 & 1
\end{vmatrix}}
{\begin{vmatrix}
  x_1 & 1\\
  x_2 & 1
\end{vmatrix}}
= \frac{y_1 - y_2}{x_1 - x_2}, 
b =
\frac{
\begin{vmatrix}
  x_1 & y_1\\
  x_2 & y_2
\end{vmatrix}}
{\begin{vmatrix}
  x_1 & 1\\
  x_2 & 1
\end{vmatrix}}
= \frac{x_1 \cdot y_2 - y_1 \cdot x_2}{x_1 - x_2}
$

We get that the **equation of a straight line constructed from two points** $(x_1, y_1), (x_2, y_2) $ has **the form**:

$
y = \frac{y_1 - y_2}{x_1 - x_2} \cdot x + \frac{x_1 \cdot y_2 - y_1 \cdot x_2}{x_1 - x_2} \Rightarrow (x_1 - x_2) \cdot y = (y_1 - y_2) \cdot x + (x_1 \cdot y_2 - y_1 \cdot x_2)
$

**It suffices to check this equality for each next point.**

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $ O(n) $
- Space complexity: $ O(1) $

# Code
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    bool checkStraightLine(vector<vector<int>>& coordinates) {
        int n = coordinates.size();
        if (n == 2) { return true; }
        int x1 = coordinates[0][0], y1 = coordinates[0][1];
        int x2 = coordinates[1][0], y2 = coordinates[1][1];
        if (x1 == x2) {
            for (int i = 2; i < n; i++) {
                if (coordinates[i][0] != x1) { return false; }
            }
            return true;
        }
        if (y1 == y2) {
            for (int i = 2; i < n; i++) {
                if (coordinates[i][1] != y1) { return false; }
            }
            return true;
        }
        int dx = x2 - x1, dy = y2 - y1, resid = x2 * y1 - x1 * y2;
        for (int i = 2; i < n; i++) {
            int x = coordinates[i][0], y = coordinates[i][1];
            if (dx * y - dy * x - resid != 0) { return false; }
        }
        return true;
    }
};
```

