solutions.content:
This problem is a variation standard LIS dp question. For each element, precompute - 

	1- The largest increasing subseq for the elements left to it, considering current element as the end series.
	2- The largest decreasing subseq(LDS) for elements right to it, considering current element as the starting of series.

Now traverse through the array, **taking each element as the peak**, then minimum number of elements that we have to delete - 

	1- On left side, which are not part of current element's LIS.
	2- On right side, which are not part of current element's LDS.

One more thing to keep in mind is that, there should be atleast one element on left and right(as given in the problem statement). Which means LIS, LDS should not be zero for current element.

Time - O(n^2)
Space - O(n)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumMountainRemovals(vector<int>& nums) {
        int i,j,n=nums.size(),ans=INT_MAX;

        vector<int>lis(n,0), lds(n,0);

		// precompute LIS with current element as the end of that sequence
        for(i=1;i<n;i++){
            for(j=0;j<i;j++)
                if(nums[i]>nums[j])
                    lis[i]=max(lis[i],lis[j]+1);
        }

		// precompute LDS with current element as start of that sequence
        for(i=n-2;i>=0;i--){
            for(j=n-1;j>i;j--)
                if(nums[i]>nums[j])
                    lds[i]=max(lds[i],lds[j]+1);
        }

        for(i=1;i<n-1;i++){
            if(lis[i]==0 || lds[i]==0 )             // to make sure that atleast one element is on both sides
                continue;

            ans = min( ans, (i-lis[i])+(n-i-1-lds[i]));     //number of elements to delete
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

