solutions.content:
This problem is the same of finding longest mountain.

First we need to form 2 arrays representing the longest increasing and decreasing subsequence from for each 0 to i in nums. (the longest decreasing subsequence is just the longest increasing subsequence of reversed nums).

For each i from 0 to n - 1, assume nums[i] is the peak, find longest increasing subsequence of nums[0:i] and longest decreasing subsequence of num[i:n-1]. The longest mountain for ith peak is the sum of them and subtract by 1 due to the duplicate count of peak.

We can filter out some elements which are not possible to be peaks
i.e. the lowest points
e.g. [2,3,**1**,5,6]
those elements having a '1' in longest increasing subsequence because none of the previous elements has lower value.

Find the maximum among the longest mountain of each peaks
Return n - max

Time complexity: O(nlogn) for lis, O(n) for finding max

```go
func lis(nums []int) []int {
    res := make([]int, len(nums))
    res[0] = 1
    ends := make([]int, 1)
    ends[0] = nums[0]
    for i := 1; i < len(nums); i++ {
        if nums[i] > ends[len(ends) - 1] {
            ends = append(ends, nums[i])
            res[i] = len(ends)
        } else {
            k := -1
            for j := len(ends) - 2; j > -1; j-- {
                if ends[j] < nums[i] {
                    k = j
                    break
                }
            }
            ends[k + 1] = nums[i]
            res[i] = k + 2
        }
    }
    return res
}

func minimumMountainRemovals(nums []int) int {
    n := len(nums)
    up := lis(nums)
    for i, j := 0, n - 1; i < j; i, j = i+1, j-1 {
        nums[i], nums[j] = nums[j], nums[i]
    }
    down := lis(nums)
    max := 0
    for i := 0; i < n; i++ {
        if up[i] == 1 || down[n-i-1] == 1 {
            continue
        }
        if up[i] + down[n-i-1] - 1 > max {
            max = up[i] + down[n-i-1] - 1
        }
    }
    return n - max
}
```

