solutions.content:
Suppose we are watching on some mountain array with **nums[i]** as a mountain element. The left part before this element is an increasing sequence, and the right part after this element is a decreasing sequence. For removing the minimum number of elements from the initial array, both sequences should be the longest possible.
Thus, for each element in the given array, we need to compute two longest sequences.
One of them is the longest increasing sequence starting from the left and ending at this element.
Another one is the longest decreasing sequence starting from the right and ending at this element.
Both tasks are well-known and can be solved using dynamic programming approach: track **dp[i]** as an answer and set it to max value from precalculated **dp[0] + 1, dp[1] + 1, dp[2] + 1, ..., dp[j] + 1, ..., dp[i - 1] + 1** for those only which has **nums[j] < nums[i]**.
After that, we need to find the max possible sum from these two values among all the elements.
```
public int minimumMountainRemovals(int[] nums) {
        int[] dp = new int[nums.length];
        dp[0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i < dp.length; i++) {
            dp[i] = 1;
            for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                if (nums[j] < nums[i]) {
                    dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        int[] dp2 = new int[nums.length];
        dp2[dp2.length - 1] = 1;
        for (int i = dp2.length - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            dp2[i] = 1;
            for (int j = dp2.length - 1; j > i; j--) {
                if (nums[j] < nums[i]) {
                    dp2[i] = Math.max(dp2[i], dp2[j] + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        int result = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < dp.length - 1; i++) {
            result = Math.max(result, dp[i] + dp2[i]);
        }
        return nums.length - result + 1;
    }
```

