# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to find all possible palindromic subsequences and choose a pair of subsequence such that none of their indices match.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We generate all possible subsequences using bit-mask. If the string is of length `n` then total number of subsequences will be `2^n`. We store only those subsequences in the hash-map which are palindromes, with their `bit-mask as key` and `length as values`.

Then we iterate through every pair of palindromic subsequence and find their product if the `AND` of their bitmask is 0.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(4^n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(2^n)

